      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Paul Krugman (column, April 26) argues that to permit multiple companies to sell Windows would amount to an expropriation of intellectual property rights and would thus set a dangerous precedent. In fact, there is ample precedent for such ''expropriation.''</p>
        <p>Our intellectual property laws, most notably the patent and copyright laws, give producers a right to exercise monopoly power over their products for a limited period of time. They are based on the principle that a limited monopoly is necessary to give people an incentive to create but that such monopoly must eventually yield to the public need for access to the new invention (or expression).</p>
        <p>Obviously, Microsoft has had significant opportunity to exploit its Windows creation monopolistically. The question under the law should be, How much is enough?</p>
        <p>CARL SUSSMAN  New York, April 26, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a lawyer.</p>
      </block>
